**Disclaimer**: I do not recommend **not** reviewing the code that AI writes. This was a deliberate year-long experiment to push AI beyond its apparent limits. If you aren’t reviewing the code, when things go wrong, you’ll struggle to know why and the AI might not be able to help you.

Note: for the rest of this article, unless otherwise stated, "AI" means "generative AI," and I'll use "AAP" for "AI-Assisted Programming."

---

# **The Journey**

## **First Steps**

I haven't talked about this much, because telling even experienced AI developers that I was on a solo quest to build production-quality code without reviewing it would lead them to see me as Quixote tilting at windmills. I'm also not a giant corporation or [a well-funded Y Combinator startup trying to pull off the same thing](https://www.hlyr.dev/) (their founder's talk on [context engineering](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IS_y40zY-hc) is excellent). I'm just one guy with limited resources.

I'll mostly skip tool-specific details, but I've tried Windsurf, Cursor, Copilot, Kiro, Spec Kit with VS Code, and have now settled on Claude Code with [Superpowers](https://github.com/obra/superpowers/), along with my PAAD skills.

My first experiments were dreadful. One project, porting some complex Perl code to Python, was a miserable failure. I figured having the Perl code as *the* source of truth meant I had a perfect spec. I did not.

I tried again, this time porting the Perl modules in dependency order, starting with the leaves of the dependency graph. I got much farther—until I discovered that my failure to review had allowed a critical design flaw into a core module that meant the system could not possibly work. It would take as much time to unravel the mess as to restart. I stopped and regrouped.

The problem was clear: there were subtle errors in my prompts, and even when there weren't, the AI wasn't writing what I asked for, sometimes adding things I did not ask for. This, compounded with AI's tendency to output slop and ignore architecture, meant that I could only scale so far.

But I wasn't giving up. I *knew* this could be done, if I could just figure out the trick.

## **The Breakthrough: Spec-Driven Development**

That's when I discovered [Spec-Driven Development](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spec-driven_development) (SDD). It's actually been around since the 1960s, but wasn't standardized until about 20 years ago. AI is merely using a well-established methodology. Specifically, I discovered [GitHub's spec-kit](https://github.com/github/spec-kit), and it turned my thinking around completely. In particular, two commands that spec-kit lists as optional: [clarify](https://github.com/github/spec-kit/blob/main/templates/commands/clarify.md) and [analyze](https://github.com/github/spec-kit/blob/main/templates/commands/analyze.md).

They are not optional.

In PAAD, these became skills named [pushback](https://github.com/Ovid/paad/blob/main/plugins/paad/skills/pushback/SKILL.md) and [alignment](https://github.com/Ovid/paad/blob/main/plugins/paad/skills/alignment/SKILL.md). Together, they were the first real breakthrough.

**Pushback** runs after you've created a spec. It looks for omissions, ambiguities, contradictions, and recent changes to the codebase that might impact your spec, presenting them one at a time so you can resolve each one. Only once have I used this skill and not had it find something.

**Alignment** takes the task list and compares it to the spec. Are all requirements addressed? Did extra "features" creep into the tasks? Your tasks must be 100% aligned with what you asked for. Even when building out specs and tasks using Claude Opus 4.6 on max thinking, I have *never* run the alignment check without it finding misalignments. Never. Not once. No matter what tool or methodology I've used, without running alignment—usually more than once—the AI is *never* building exactly what I asked for.

This was a critical discovery. The AI doesn't betray you with obviously wrong code. It betrays you with almost-right code that does slightly more, or slightly less, than what you specified. Pushback and alignment catch these drifts before they compound.

I was asked if I thought SDD was the "end goal" of AAP. I don't believe it is. We're still discovering and exploring. PAAD is an interim solution, covering gaps with AAP. As we push further, I fully expect—and hope—that it will become unnecessary.

Pretty confident in my newfound skills, I set out to create [Tramp Freighter Blues](/paad/tramp-freighter/), a browser-based space trading game (about 30K lines of JavaScript and [Three.js](http://Three.js), or 95K if you count the tests, too). You can [play the game and read the code](https://github.com/Ovid/tramp-freighter) and judge for yourself. (Note: it can run on mobile, but it's unplayable—it was designed for a full browser.)

